The Fragility of a Flat World
The World Is Flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman said so. Friedman chose this highly provocative title for his best-selling book in order to make people aware of the astonishing impact technology has had on the world economy.
Distance is shrinking.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide security.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States have all had to face the challenges of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak to are likely to be far away in India.
Skeptics pointed out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but rather "uneven."
The topographic map of global economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Moreover, distance has far from lost its significance.
Even neighboring countries with lower tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, have far more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, yet Vancouver's trade with the more distant Toronto far exceeds its trade with the nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman presents an important point.
Globalization can be defined as mutual dependence between different continents, a history as long as human history itself, witnessing the migration of races and religions, as well as trade along the ancient Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different, developing at a faster pace and reaching a deeper level.
After the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid in 1868, Europe and the United States could communicate within just one minute.
In 1919, the economist John Maynard Keynes depicted a British person living in London ordering goods from all over the world by telephone, then sitting at home waiting to receive them in the afternoon.
But Keynes's British person was a rare exception of the wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy products from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, instant global communication emerged 20 years ago, but it was economically beyond the reach of the majority of people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an Internet café and gain access to capabilities that were once available only to governments, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or institutions with large budgets.
The significant decline in the costs of computation, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly accessible.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of Internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, Internet users in the United States account for less than a quarter of the global user base.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached the highest level in human history.
Non-state institutions now possess capabilities that were once held exclusively by governments.
The status of the nation-state as a political actor in the world will not change anytime soon, but it must learn to share this vast stage with a growing number of participants, including organizations such as the Oxford Committee for Famine Relief, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks such as Al-Qaeda.
But this flattening process is reversible.
Similar things have happened before.
The world economy was once highly integrated in 1914, but over the next 30 years, economic interdependence among nations steadily declined.
It wasn't until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had once achieved, though it was still heavily divided by the Iron Curtain.
World War I served as the catalyst for the reversal, and during the two world wars and one global Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and a rise in military globalization.
This reflected deeper issues of domestic inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in the rise of abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—which split the nation and the world into pieces.
After World War II, the welfare state system in the West provided a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the rewards of international economic interdependence.
Some analysts argue that China's role today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising forces troubled by domestic inequality, constantly moving toward nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and ultimately triggering world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, weren't the economies of Britain and Germany similarly interdependent before 1914?
But such reasoning is not sound.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
However, even with maintaining this high growth rate, China's economy is unlikely to catch up with the United States within at least 20 years.
A greater threat to the flat world may be the non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in an unannounced attack than the Japanese government did in its Pearl Harbor attack in 1941.
I refer to this phenomenon as the privatization of war.
If such forces gain access to nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a dramatic transformation.
At that time, it would have been more difficult for people and goods to cross borders.
If such forces disrupted the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic downturn similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen protectionist forces.
Technology and policy are the two major driving forces of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effects of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States holds a leading position in promoting policies to eliminate barriers.
But the events described above could reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization may be willing to see such an outcome.
But such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situation in two areas—namely, the reversal of the economic globalization trend driven by the spread of technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization would be further consolidated, such as war, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that is the case, the flat world would become a desert.
